<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is tangential vs radial shrinkage?", answer: "Tangential shrinkage is movement across the growth rings, which is the largest direction of wood movement. Radial shrinkage is movement toward the pith, or center of the tree, and is typically about half the tangential value. Longitudinal shrinkage along the length of the grain is negligible at less than 0.2 percent and is ignored for practical purposes. Flatsawn boards move primarily tangentially, while quartersawn boards move primarily radially and are dimensionally more stable." },
  { question: "Why does wood only shrink below 30% MC?", answer: "Wood fibers contain two types of water: free water in the cell cavities and bound water within the cell walls. As wood dries, free water evaporates first with no change in dimension. Once all free water is gone at about 30 percent moisture content, known as the fiber saturation point, bound water begins to leave the cell walls, which causes the cells to shrink. All dimensional change happens between the fiber saturation point and the final moisture content." },
  { question: "Which species move the least?", answer: "Teak and genuine mahogany have the lowest shrinkage values among common furniture woods, with total tangential shrinkage around 4 percent. Spanish cedar, eastern white pine, and western red cedar are also very stable. High-shrinkage species include American beech, hickory, and white oak, which can move more than 10 percent tangentially from green to oven dry. Quartersawn lumber of any species will be more stable than flatsawn." },
  { question: "How do I allow for wood movement in joinery?", answer: "Never glue or fasten solid wood panels rigidly across the grain. Use breadboard ends with elongated slots, floating panels in frame-and-panel construction, tabletop fasteners that allow sliding, or wooden buttons in grooves. Always let wood acclimate to its final environment before building. Orient grain consistently so adjoining parts move together. Plan for seasonal changes of roughly 1/4 inch of movement per 12 inches of width for typical hardwoods." },
  { question: "Does sealing wood stop shrinkage?", answer: "Finishes slow moisture exchange but do not prevent it over the long term. Even film finishes like polyurethane and lacquer allow water vapor to pass through slowly, so wood will still move with seasonal humidity changes just more gradually. End grain sealers help prevent rapid drying and checking, and finishing all sides of a panel equally helps prevent cupping, but no finish can eliminate wood movement entirely." }
]) %>

